{% # Color contrast v2.0.0 %}

{% comment %}
  Changelog
  - v2.0.0 — rename params for clarity: `color` → `background` (says what it is); `black` / `white` → `dark` / `light` (semantic intent, not hardcoded labels). Tie-breaking now favors the dark reference (`>=` instead of `>`) — matches the canonical reading-direction convention (dark-on-light) and the browser default text color. Consumers update the keyword in the render call (`color:` → `background:`); no other behavior change.
  - v1.0.0 — initial
{% endcomment %}

{% doc %}
  @description Returns whichever of two reference colors has the higher computed contrast against the input `background`. Echoes a hex string suitable for direct interpolation into a CSS value (e.g. inside a custom property declaration).

  Wraps Liquid's native `color_contrast` filter, which returns a 0–21 contrast ratio. Used by validation pages to pick a legible foreground per theme color.

  @param {color} background - The background color the contrast is computed against. Defaults to `#ffffff`.
  @param {color} [dark] - Darker reference color compared against `background`. Defaults to `#000000`.
  @param {color} [light] - Lighter reference color compared against `background`. Defaults to `#ffffff`.

  @example {% render 'utility--color-contrast', background: section.settings.background %}
  @example {% capture fg %}{% render 'utility--color-contrast', background: '#cc0033' %}{% endcapture %}
{% enddoc %}

{% liquid
  assign background = background | default: '#ffffff'
  assign dark = dark | default: '#000000'
  assign light = light | default: '#ffffff'

  assign dark_contrast = background | color_contrast: dark
  assign light_contrast = background | color_contrast: light

  if dark_contrast >= light_contrast
    echo dark
  else
    echo light
  endif
%}
